</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="66E65659AA5F71CE78CAE894E59174CB" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="F71CAC5CF63BF1E9E5682DFC0D82F776" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
The types of 
<taxonomicName id="58CDF2CE03F2CB70FF4BA72D59EA8305" authority="Berlese, 1885" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1885" class="Arachnida" family="Lohmanniidae" genus="Angelia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Oribatida" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ornatissima">Angelia ornatissima</taxonomicName>
(viz. the nos. 81/9, 15 from Lake City, Florida) are still present in the collection. The species certainly belongs to the genus 
<taxonomicName id="3B582D70DE262511F4D3D3FDD420793C" class="Arachnida" family="Camisiidae" genus="Heminothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Heminothrus</taxonomicName>
; the figure will probably be sufficient for purposes of identification. The length is 0.585-0.600, and the breadth 0.290 mm; according to Berlese the measurements are 0.650 X 0.330 mm, in which the hairs are possibly included.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17112034056D0BAE0D5EED2755D6F4FA" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5DF173A21E62F23AAB837838692D7BF0" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
I remark that Berlese (1913) did not mention the species as a representative of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="B72F6FE1F7F0C3506C218C464594143A" class="Arachnida" family="Nothridae" genus="Nothrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Heminothrus">Heminothrus</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
